  "summary": "After Bartle suggests that Anthony needs help from both himself and the deceptive Mrs. Reeve, Anthony returns to his upstairs room. There, he discovers an intact, unopened bundle of letters signed by Virginia Reveaux sitting on his vanity. Confused, Anthony questions how the letters returned to the villa and who placed them there.\n\nAt 10 a.m., the Earl of Carrington and his daughter, Bandel, have breakfast. Bandel questions her father about a man she saw eating alone. The Earl explains that he spoke with the sheriff, who stated that anyone wishing to leave the villa may do so, though the sheriff also hoped guests would stay. The Earl mentions he has invited \"Kid\" to stay and is arranging for Azerbaijan to take a 10:50 train to London. He expresses a desire to be rid of Fitch, whom he finds boring because Fitch never offers opinions. Bandel and the Earl discuss various guests, including George Romax and Virginia. The Earl expresses doubt regarding his relationship with Virginia, noting that while she is gentle, her words may lack true meaning.\n\nLater, Mr. Hale Fiskle approaches the Earl to ask if the ban on leaving has been lifted. The Earl invites him to stay, and Fiskle accepts, citing an interest in studying the English countryside. The Earl then encounters Virginia in the living room. She declines his offer to accompany her to breakfast, stating she has already eaten in bed. The Earl invites her to stay longer, which she accepts. Virginia then goes into the garden, where she is startled by the sudden appearance of Constable Bartle. She remarks that despite a lack of sleep, the previous night was exciting.",
